title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith and Wesson S&W K200 Victory/Pre-Victory .38 S&W CTG Revolver
postcontent:
I am open to other trades, let me know what you have.

A .38 S&W K200 Victory model revolver. This is the forerunner to the .38 special we know today. This particular revolver is a .38/200 British Service Revolver made by Smith and Wesson in the USA. It has a 5 inch pinned barrel and was made somewhere around 1943. Most of these revolvers went to England around this time but there are no proof marks on this to suggest a military or export model but it does have the original lanyard ring. It has the original grips with silver medallions. It does not have the "V" serial number prefix or the "US Property" mark meaning it was most likely a civilian model. I never lettered it from Smith and Wesson to find out any details since it was bound to be a restoration piece for me. This gun was never converted to .38 special after the war like a lot were and is chambered for the .38 S&W (short .38). According to experts the serial number puts it in the range of the later hardened steel cylinders so if you decided to shoot this beauty it can take modern .38 S&W ammo, NOT .38 Special though! It was expertly refinished, and the hammer and trigger (re)case hardened by Ford's in Florida, the best of the best. 

Here's what I need:

I am searching for a Remington Model 700 8mm Rem Mag for a project. That would be my first choice. Any long action Remington 700 would work for me but I would prefer a stainless Sendero if there is such out there. I believe there are in 7mm Rem Mag. Anyway, I'm open to cash offers and trades like I suggested. I put the price at what I consider its trade value. Let me know what ya got! Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P228 9mm x 19 Para (German) w/2 clips (13 cap.)

Original owner since 2/91 this gun was only used twice at the range, approx. 100 total rounds fired. Stored in gun case and cleaned/oiled twice a year. It's in excellent condition. Sorry but the original box is not available however will include 100 rounds of ammunition & Bianchi Model 7506 thurmbsnap belt slide holster (both items valued at $65+)

Review: SIG P228 Review articled in "THE ARMS SITE"
Reliability:
The SIG P228 is supremely reliable out of the box. Its reliability can only be matched by the P226 and arguably bested by the Beretta 92.

Accuracy:
Every SIG P228 I've shot is accurate enough to reach out and touch a target to 100 yards with confidence. This can't be said for many other popular pistols. The only popular service pistol that beats the P228 for accuracy out of the box is the SIG P226.

How it shoots:
If you are a federal agent(Secret Service standard issue), intelligence operative, law enforcement officer or civilian possessing a SIG P228, don't feel shortchanged or undergunned. You're carrying one of the best pistols made. World-class reliable, accurate, ergonomic and easily controllable, you can't get much better. Stick with it, practice often and with realism, and know that this gun will hold up its end of the bargain when you need it to.
